		<div id="comment-15260">
		<div class="commentnumber">43</div>		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/a890daaba11af8548861d4e0d6fa6adc?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.loveandoliveoil.com%2Fwp-content%2Fthemes%2Flaoo2012%2Fimages%2Fgravatar.png%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />		<div class="commentauthor">Kara</div>
		<div class="commentmeta"><em>Posted On</em> January 15, 2010 <em>at</em> <a href="#comment-15260">10:54 am</a> <!--<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/01/chocolate-chip-cookie-dough-truffles.html?replytocom=15260#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-15260", "15260", "respond", "1979")'>Reply</a>--> 		</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
		<div class="comment-body"><p>These are AWESOME! When I make cookies, I always end up eating half the dough anyway, so these are perfect for me!<br />
I became very popular at work after bringing some of these for people to try :)</p>
<p>I used dark chocolate for the coating and it worked well &#8212; If you melt it gently enough, it will stay tempered &#8212; I melted in the microwave (gently 30 seconds at a time, stirring in between) until glossy but chunky, and then just kept stirring to melt the last little bits.</p>
<p>I found this online article helpful for tempering tips:<br />
<a href="http://www.cookingforengineers.com/article/155/Tempering-Chocolate" rel="nofollow">http://www.cookingforengineers.com/article/155/Tempering-Chocolate</a></p>
<p class="thdrpy"><a href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="movecfm(event,15260,1,'Kara');">Reply</a></p></div>
